            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this SIP calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                A Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) lets you invest a fixed
                amount at regular intervals (usually monthly) into a mutual fund
                or other investment product. This calculator helps you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Estimate the <strong>future value</strong> of a SIP given your
                  monthly amount, tenure, and expected return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Find the <strong>required SIP amount</strong> to reach a
                  target corpus by a certain date.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Model a <strong>step-up SIP</strong> where your contribution
                  increases every year.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formula for SIP maturity amount</h3>
              <p>
                For a regular SIP with fixed periodic investment \( P \),
                constant periodic return \( r \), and \( n \) total instalments,
                the future value (maturity amount) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{FV} = P \times \frac{(1 + r)^n - 1}{r} \times (1 + r)
                \)
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>\( P \) = SIP amount per instalment (e.g. per month)</li>
                <li>
                  \( r \) = periodic rate of return (annual rate ÷ 12 for
                  monthly SIP)
                </li>
                <li>
                  \( n \) = total number of instalments (years × 12 for monthly
                  SIP)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The extra \( (1 + r) \) factor assumes each SIP instalment is
                made at the <em>beginning</em> of the period (common in SIP
                illustrations).
              </p>

              <h3>Formula for required SIP to reach a goal</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the target future value \( \text{FV} \), the
                required periodic SIP amount \( P \) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( P = \dfrac{\text{FV}}{\left(\dfrac{(1 + r)^n - 1}{r}\right)
                \times (1 + r)} \)
              </div>

              <h3>Step-up SIP calculation</h3>
              <p>
                In a step-up SIP, your monthly contribution increases by a fixed
                percentage every year (for example 10%). The calculator
                simulates each month individually:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Applies the current monthly SIP amount.</li>
                <li>Grows the accumulated corpus by the monthly return.</li>
                <li>
                  At each 12-month boundary, increases the SIP amount by the
                  chosen step-up percentage.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This gives a realistic projection of how increasing
                contributions can accelerate wealth creation.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting the results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total invested</strong> – the sum of all SIP
                  instalments you contribute.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Maturity value</strong> – the projected value of your
                  investment at the end of the tenure.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wealth gained</strong> – maturity value minus total
                  invested (the effect of compounding).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The year-by-year schedule shows how your investment grows over
                time, which years contribute most to wealth creation, and how
                much of the final corpus comes from your own contributions
                versus returns.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator assumes a
                  <strong>constant annual return</strong> converted to a
                  periodic rate; real markets are volatile.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It ignores
                  <strong>taxes, exit loads, and expense ratios</strong> of
                  mutual funds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Inflation is not factored in; you may want to use a lower
                  “real” return to account for it.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are for
                  <strong>illustration and planning</strong> only, not
                  guaranteed returns or investment advice.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

