              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">
                SIP Calculator – Frequently Asked Questions
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium">What is a SIP calculator?</span>
                    <span class="text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    A SIP calculator is a planning tool that estimates how much
                    your regular investments can grow over time. You enter your
                    monthly SIP amount, expected annual return, and investment
                    period, and the calculator shows the projected maturity
                    value, total invested amount, and wealth gained.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Is SIP better than lump sum investment?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Neither is universally better. A lump sum invested at once
                    benefits more from compounding if markets rise steadily. SIP
                    spreads your investments over time, which reduces timing
                    risk and can average out market volatility. Many investors
                    use a combination of both depending on when they receive
                    cash flows.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Can I change my SIP amount later?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Most mutual fund platforms allow you to increase, decrease,
                    or stop your SIP. This calculator supports that idea through
                    the step-up SIP mode, where you can model a fixed annual
                    increase. For irregular changes, you can run multiple
                    scenarios with different SIP amounts and tenures.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How often should I review my SIP plan?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Reviewing once a year is a good practice. Check whether your
                    income has increased (so you can step up your SIP), whether
                    your goals or timelines have changed, and whether the
                    assumed return is still realistic for your chosen funds.
                  </div>
                </div>
